  "prompt": "An atom has electrons, protons and neutrons. But what's in the electrons, protons or neutrons?",
  "response": "Electrons, protons, and neutrons are fundamental particles, but they are not all indivisible. Here's a breakdown of what they are made of:\n\n1. **Electrons**: Electrons are considered elementary particles in the Standard Model of particle physics, meaning they are not made up of smaller components. They have no known substructure and are classified as **leptons**.\n\n2. **Protons and Neutrons**: Protons and neutrons are not elementary particles. They are composed of smaller particles called **quarks**, which are held together by the **strong nuclear force** mediated by particles called **gluons**.\n   - **Protons**: Made up of two **up quarks** and one **down quark**.\n   - **Neutrons**: Made up of two **down quarks** and one **up quark**.\n\nProtons and neutrons are collectively called **nucleons** and are part of the **baryon** family of particles in the **hadron** class. The quarks inside them are bound together by gluons, which are the carriers of the strong force.\n\nIn summary:\n- Electrons are elementary particles with no substructure.\n- Protons and neutrons are made of quarks held together by gluons.",
